                <head>121. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On June 11, <persName corresp="#p_NGL1">General Norstad</persName>, Supreme
                    Allied Commander, Europe, informed the <gloss target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss> of
                    his plan to redeploy nine U.S. Air Force squadrons in France because of the
                    unwillingness of France to agree to stockpile the required atomic weapons. After
                    this report, the French Representative stated that his country would not grant
                    nuclear storage rights until it received satisfaction on French aspirations for
                    participation in worldwide strategic planning. While recognizing <persName
                        corresp="#p_NGL1">Norstad</persName>’s concern about common security risks,
                    the French Representative maintained that France could not make additional
                    commitments in <gloss target="#t_NATO1">NATO</gloss> which had no reference to
                    global necessities. (<gloss target="#t_Polto1">Polto</gloss> Circular 45, <pb
                        facs="0271" n="235" xml:id="pg_235"/> June 11; Department of State, Central
                    Files, 740.5/6–1159) On July 8, the United States announced to the <gloss
                        target="#t_NAC1">NAC</gloss> its decision to redeploy these squadrons.
                        (<gloss target="#t_Polto1">Polto</gloss> 62, July 8; <hi rend="italic"
                        >ibid</hi>., 711.56351/7–859)</p>
                <p>For additional documentation on these questions, see <ref
                        target="frus1958-60v07p1#d213">Part 1, Documents 213</ref> ff.</p>
            </div>
